#We will examine the data by Departments to focus on any specific detailed information #We will look at the Sales department specifically here in this section ## We can see here that Attrition did occur in the Sales Department, so we will look at their survey results. #We discover from the Relationship Plot with Attrition; we discover that people with the Manager Job Role on average did not have well relationships with their superiors.

#We also wanted to look at the people who currently still works at the firm and how their surveys looked. #We discover on average their surveys whether it was relationship satisfaction, job involvement, or job satisfaction they had an overall wonderful experience.

#So, we would need to keep in the back of our mind, what would cause these employees to leave when the Sales Department as a group tends to have overall high surveys across all Job Levels and Job Roles they have within the department. #Could this be a money, distance from work, stock options, etc.? We will have to dig further, but for now we will look at this same survey for other departments.

#In this section we will examine the Research & Development Department. We would want to look at people who did leave the company if any, and the people who are currently with them. #The Job Involvement for former employees on average their surveys seem to be between 2-3 (Moderately Happy) on average regardless of the job levels for each job role. This could be a potential reason factor in employees leaving, we would have to examine further on Job Involvement. #We also look at the Job Satisfaction where the job levels 2, 3 and 5 seems to have low survey scores. Job Satisfaction overall could lead to a factor on why people would leave because they would feel unhappy with their responsibilities. #The relationship Satisfaction between employee and manager or executive seems to over lab across all job levels with the average leaning below 3 (Moderately happy). We see that Research Scientist specifically is overall job level 1 seems to have scored two.

#In this section we will examine the HR Department. We would want to look at similar aspect compared to the other two departments we examined. #In this section we see there are only two job roles in this department, one labeled Human Resources and the other labeled Manager #We also see the people who are now former employees are only Human Resources Job Roles. #Their overall Relationship Satisfaction between employee and managers on average seems to be around the grade 3 (Happy). We will need to examine further what other factors caused these employees to leave.

#After discovering interesting facts about variables that could be factors in attrition. Now we will look at majority of the variables here to see which variables are correlated between each other. If these variables are correlated between each other then we would need to take them out and not use them in our potential model. This is since multiple factors trying to explain our model in the next section will not achieve anything and could be overfitting the model. We were able to find a model that best fit and look at the evidence to back up our model. We will also conduct a classification model with Naive Bayes to see sensitivity and specificity.

#In conclusion, we discovered that the main factors that leads to attrition are Job Satisfaction, Job Level, Job Involvement, OverTime, Martial Status, and Years in Current Role. These appear to have great significance in whether a employee would stay with the company or leave. Perhaps the company can focus on these areas of weakness and discover what is cause low survey scores that is causing attrition. There could be number of reasons, it will be difficult to narrow it down to only one. The former employees could be poor performers in the workplace which could have an impact on productivity. Any company would not want high attrition rate due to its cost like hiring replacements and training them.
